WEBVTT

00:00.334 --> 00:02.568
     ADULT ADAM:
     <i> Back in the '80s,</i>
     <i> the most terrifying place</i>

00:02.570 --> 00:06.739
 <i> in existence for any freshman</i>
 <i> was the high-school cafeteria.</i>

00:06.741 --> 00:09.308
    <i> The table you chose defined</i>
    <i> how you were labeled</i>

00:09.310 --> 00:11.477
      <i> and where you ranked</i>
      <i> in the social hierarchy.</i>

00:11.479 --> 00:14.079
           I don't see
           any seats together.
           What should we do?

00:14.081 --> 00:15.014
 Every man for himself.

00:15.016 --> 00:17.883
 If anyone asks,
 I'm a skate rat now.

00:20.388 --> 00:20.919
    Ooh.

00:20.921 --> 00:22.788
           ADULT ADAM:
           <i> Classic Dave Kim.</i>

00:22.790 --> 00:24.456
 Figuring out
 where to sit, eh?

00:24.458 --> 00:28.227
                    Yeah.
      Ah, that's a sad dance
      that I know all too well.

00:28.229 --> 00:30.229
      But lucky for you,
      I'm a guidance counselor,

00:30.231 --> 00:32.430
          and I can guide you
          to lunchroom success.

00:32.433 --> 00:34.366
          Um, maybe I could sit
          with the preppies?

00:34.368 --> 00:37.870
 Come on, man.
 You want to walk around
 in boat shoes with no socks?

00:37.872 --> 00:40.406
   You want to invite that kind
   of fungus in your life?

00:40.408 --> 00:42.207
         Okay. How about
         the band geeks?

00:42.209 --> 00:45.144
           Do you even play
           an instrument?
           No, you don't.

00:45.146 --> 00:47.713
 So what makes you think
 they're gonna just welcome you

00:47.715 --> 00:49.848
            into their unique
            and beautiful fold?

00:49.850 --> 00:52.217
                 Uh, maybe
                 the Goth kids?

00:52.219 --> 00:54.553
      The Goths?
      They would eat you alive.

00:54.555 --> 00:56.522
       Seriously, I heard
       they eat cats and stuff.

00:56.524 --> 00:59.291
         Come on!
         I gotta sit somewhere!
         Time's running out!

00:59.293 --> 01:01.527
    Agreed. And you're starting
    to look real desperate,

01:01.529 --> 01:03.495
        and standing next to me
        is not helping you.

01:03.497 --> 01:05.230
              Please, just go!
          Mmm, okay.

01:05.232 --> 01:07.099
    ADULT ADAM:
    <i> I was officially tableless.</i>

01:07.101 --> 01:08.467
       <i> If I didn't find</i>
       <i> a place to sit,</i>

01:08.469 --> 01:10.636
   <i> I'd be</i>
   <i> a social pariah forever.</i>

01:10.638 --> 01:12.438
              Hey, Goldberg,
              come sit with us.

01:12.440 --> 01:14.306
        <i> Just then the sportos</i>
        <i> beckon me</i>

01:14.308 --> 01:16.642
    <i> to sit at the coolest table</i>
    <i> in the cafeteria.</i>

01:16.644 --> 01:19.812
     <i> It was either a miracle</i>
     <i> or a huge mistake.</i>

01:19.814 --> 01:20.979
      Grab a chair, little man.

01:20.981 --> 01:22.681
  And the plate of waffle fries
  is for sharing.

01:22.683 --> 01:26.885
         No offense to myself,
         but I think you got
         the wrong guy.

01:26.887 --> 01:27.152
                        No way!

01:27.154 --> 01:32.357
      We all think it's awesome
      that you're super into
      movies, robots, He-Man.

01:32.359 --> 01:33.826
             Oh, so you're also
             a He-head?

01:33.828 --> 01:36.528
     That's the name I've given
     to die-hard He-Man fans.

01:36.530 --> 01:40.032
 That's cool.
 It's also cool that, like,

01:40.034 --> 01:42.000
 the top of your head
 smells so good.

01:42.002 --> 01:44.069
            Odd observation
            from that distance,

01:44.071 --> 01:45.704
  but I do condition every day.

01:45.706 --> 01:47.272
     It shows, bro.
                         Nice.

01:47.274 --> 01:48.207
 Such luster.

01:48.209 --> 01:49.775
                Ah, balls!
                She got to you!

01:49.777 --> 01:52.411
 No, man. We...
 We like you for you.

01:52.413 --> 01:55.180
        God, my own mom
        has to find me a table?

01:55.182 --> 01:55.981
       That's where my life is?

01:55.983 --> 01:57.382
 She gave us free waffle fries.
 You get it.

01:57.384 --> 02:02.020
         She also yelled at us
         and said that in time,
         we'd come to love you.

02:02.323 --> 02:04.723
 Mom, I don't want
 to hear any more!

02:04.725 --> 02:05.457
        Adam.

02:05.459 --> 02:06.024
            Mom,
            you ruined my life!

02:06.026 --> 02:09.495
 Schmoo, you just
 seemed so helpless
 without a place to sit.

02:09.497 --> 02:11.630
 It's my job,
 as your mama, to help.

02:11.632 --> 02:14.266
      Help?
      That's the whole problem.

02:14.268 --> 02:15.434
            If you're gonna sub
            at my school,

02:15.436 --> 02:18.470
      you have to start
      respecting my boundaries.
      Understand?

02:18.472 --> 02:20.038
 Boundaries.
 Totally get it.

02:20.040 --> 02:20.606
                  Do you?
 Boundaries.

02:20.608 --> 02:23.742
       'Cause nothing up
       to this point has led me
       to believe you do.

02:23.744 --> 02:24.376
 I get boundaries, Adam.

02:24.378 --> 02:28.413
  You don't want me
  to intervene or talk to you
  while you're at school.

02:28.415 --> 02:29.915
                  Good.
 Until I see you struggle,

02:29.917 --> 02:32.117
 and then I come in
 strong and hard.

02:32.119 --> 02:33.285
               Nope. Lost it.
 Okay, okay.

02:33.287 --> 02:36.588
 We'll limit our interactions
 to hallway snuggies...

02:36.590 --> 02:38.891
                     Mom!
 ...and brief
 Eskimo kisses.

02:38.893 --> 02:39.758
                     Mom.
 Grr. Fine.

02:39.760 --> 02:41.326
 I'll leave your little
 kitten nose alone.

02:41.328 --> 02:44.096
               Thank you.
  But at home,
  all bets are off.

02:44.098 --> 02:45.330
                     No!

02:45.332 --> 02:46.265
      <i> � I'm twisted up inside</i>

02:46.267 --> 02:50.068
       <i> � But nonetheless</i>
       <i> I feel the need to say</i>

02:52.673 --> 02:53.539
     <i> � I don't know the future</i>

02:53.541 --> 02:57.943
   <i> � But the past keeps getting</i>
   <i> clearer every day �</i>

02:58.112 --> 03:00.012
        ADULT ADAM:
        <i> It was October 12,</i>
        <i> 1980-something,</i>

03:00.014 --> 03:03.549
   <i> and my dad was coming home</i>
   <i> to a familiar frustration.</i>

03:03.551 --> 03:05.017
 Did anyone call
 while I was out?

03:05.019 --> 03:06.318
 Yeah. I wrote it down
 on the pad.

03:06.320 --> 03:08.520
  Flurt Burtman?
  Who the hell's Flurt Burtman?

03:08.522 --> 03:11.490
 I don't know.
 He was talking all fast,
 'cause it was important.

03:11.492 --> 03:13.292
 Anyway,
 call him back.
 Call who back?

03:13.294 --> 03:16.261
 If it's important,
 I need to know
 the actual name.

03:16.263 --> 03:19.031
 I don't know.
 I'm not invested,
 because it wasn't for me.

03:19.033 --> 03:21.166
 What the hell's
 this message? "PP"?

03:21.168 --> 03:21.700
 Oh, Barry wrote that.

03:21.702 --> 03:25.504
 My guess is he either
 drank too much Mr. Pibb
 or Pop Pop called?

03:25.506 --> 03:26.838
           Wait. My dad called?

03:26.840 --> 03:27.739
       He never uses the phone.

03:27.741 --> 03:29.575
      He always thinks
      the Cubans are listening.

03:29.577 --> 03:30.475
 Oh, he calls
 all the time.

03:30.477 --> 03:32.945
 He just says, "Tell the moron
 I'll call him back."

03:32.947 --> 03:35.514
 Oh, so this is me giving you
 those dozens of messages.

03:35.516 --> 03:38.383
        You know what?
        This madness stops now.

03:38.385 --> 03:40.052
        ADULT ADAM:
        <i> My dad's solution...</i>

03:40.054 --> 03:40.986
   <i> The answering machine.</i>

03:40.988 --> 03:42.688
       <i> Before voicemail,</i>
       <i> this bulky thing</i>

03:42.690 --> 03:45.857
    <i> was the best technology</i>
    <i> the '80s had to offer.</i>

03:45.859 --> 03:46.758
               Problem solved.

03:46.760 --> 03:49.995
 Holy crap! You got us
 an answering machine?

03:49.997 --> 03:51.029
 Erica, come quick!

03:51.031 --> 03:52.898
 Dad did something
 that doesn't suck!

03:52.900 --> 03:54.600
          Oh, my God!
          An answering machine?

03:54.602 --> 03:57.102
              Stop, you morons.
              It's not for you.

03:57.104 --> 03:59.338
          It's so I can finally
          get my messages.

03:59.340 --> 04:00.205
      I'm doing
      the outgoing message.

04:00.207 --> 04:02.407
 No way! I've been planning
 for this my whole life.

04:02.409 --> 04:05.377
 (AS MR. T)
 I don't want
 no jibber-jabber, foo'!

04:05.379 --> 04:06.144
 Wait for the beep!

04:06.146 --> 04:07.746
 Stay in school,
 and leave a message.

04:07.748 --> 04:10.015
 This is Mr. T,
 by the way.
 Get out of here.

04:10.017 --> 04:12.517
     (AS TONY MONTANA)
     Say hello
     to my little message.

04:12.519 --> 04:15.687
      This is Scarface,
      by the way. Cocaine.

04:15.689 --> 04:17.022
                   I'm leaving
                   the message.

04:17.024 --> 04:18.357
           There's a simple one
           right here

04:18.358 --> 04:19.757
     in the instruction book.
           No! It can't be you!

04:19.760 --> 04:21.627
 (NORMAL VOICE)
 No! Don't read
 the suggested script!

04:21.629 --> 04:22.427
        That's the worst option
        of all.

04:22.429 --> 04:25.764
          Hello. You've reached
          the answering machine

04:25.766 --> 04:27.499
            of the
            Goldberg residence.

04:27.501 --> 04:31.436
      We either are unavailable
      or unable

04:31.438 --> 04:32.871
            to get to the phone
            at the moment,

04:32.873 --> 04:35.040
     but we would appreciate it
     if you would leave

04:35.042 --> 04:37.843
   your name, telephone number,
   business,

04:37.845 --> 04:42.180
 the person you're calling for,
 and the time you called

04:42.182 --> 04:44.249
       after you hear the beep.

04:44.251 --> 04:47.653
   And we will be sure
   to get back to you at our...

04:47.655 --> 04:48.920
        Come on! Everyone knows
        how to do it.

04:48.922 --> 04:50.856
 I can't take it.
 It's so long and explain-y.

04:50.858 --> 04:52.124
                  Shut up!

04:52.126 --> 04:53.825
          Earliest convenience.

04:53.827 --> 04:56.561
       (CHUCKLES) Yeah.
       I... I'm good with that.

04:56.563 --> 04:58.297
      ADULT ADAM:
      <i> As my dad got the win,</i>

04:58.299 --> 05:00.599
    <i> I was still a lone loser</i>
    <i> without a table.</i>

05:00.601 --> 05:02.334
     <i> My only choice</i>
     <i> was to accept my fate</i>

05:02.336 --> 05:03.902
      <i> of eating alone</i>
      <i> under the bleachers.</i>

05:03.904 --> 05:07.639
 <i> That is, until I stumbled upon</i>
 <i> my salvation.</i>

05:07.641 --> 05:09.841
              Holy motherboard.

05:09.843 --> 05:11.176
  <i> The high-school computer lab.</i>

05:11.178 --> 05:13.412
  <i> It had six state-of-the-art</i>
  <i> Apple IIs,</i>

05:13.414 --> 05:17.549
 <i> each with double floppy drives</i>
 <i> and a dot-matrix printer</i>

05:17.551 --> 05:19.685
 <i> that could ink a</i>
 <i> whopping six lines per minute</i>

05:19.687 --> 05:22.220
 <i> on that weird paper</i>
 <i> where you rip off the sides.</i>

05:22.222 --> 05:24.222
   We're allowed
   to be in here.
              Okay.

05:24.224 --> 05:26.692
  Mr. Glascott says we can stay
  the whole lunch period

05:26.694 --> 05:27.959
            as long as we don't
            make crumbs,

05:27.961 --> 05:30.962
   which is why I bring
   a thermos of soup every day.

05:30.964 --> 05:32.264
        Cool.

05:32.266 --> 05:33.598
 Whoa. Is that
 <i> Prince of Persia?</i>

05:33.600 --> 05:36.435
          We've got it all...
          <i> Castle Wolfenstein,</i>
          <i> Lode Runner,</i>

05:36.437 --> 05:39.938
    <i> Choplifter,</i>  and <i> Ultima,</i>
    parts I, II, III, and IV.

05:39.940 --> 05:42.674
 You have part IV?
 That's the ultimate "Ultima"!

05:42.676 --> 05:44.776
           You know your stuff.
 I'm Adam, by the way.

05:44.778 --> 05:46.912
        I'm Mike Levy.
        This is also Mike Levy.

05:46.914 --> 05:48.080
 You guys have
 the same name?

05:48.082 --> 05:49.981
              Yeah, but Mike Z.
              is painfully shy,

05:49.983 --> 05:51.550
               so it's not much
               of an issue.

05:51.552 --> 05:55.454
 I feel your pain.
 There's a senior also
 named Adam Goldberg.

05:55.456 --> 05:57.756
 He's not happy
 to have me around.

05:57.758 --> 05:58.457
           (CHUCKLES) Right on.

05:58.459 --> 06:00.625
 I'm actually pretty good
 at <i> Oregon Trail.</i>

06:00.627 --> 06:02.594
    ADULT ADAM:
    <i> Even though I immediately</i>
    <i> died of dysentery,</i>

06:02.596 --> 06:05.430
  <i> my mom was thrilled I found</i>
  <i> a party to hitch my wagon to.</i>

06:05.432 --> 06:09.301
  <i> Meanwhile, Erica and Barry</i>
  <i> were blazing their own trail.</i>

06:09.303 --> 06:10.001
        ERICA:
        Guess what we have.

06:10.003 --> 06:13.238
  The answers to all our
  answering-machine problems...

06:13.240 --> 06:14.206
       BOTH: Crazy Calls.

06:14.208 --> 06:16.508
       I don't know what it is,
       but it sounds wild.

06:16.510 --> 06:19.311
 It's a tape of professionally
 recorded outgoing messages

06:19.313 --> 06:20.979
 that represent
 many musical styles.

06:20.981 --> 06:24.449
     And it's advertised on TV,
     so you know it's good.

06:24.451 --> 06:26.251
     BARRY: Prepare yourselves.

06:26.253 --> 06:28.954
        MAN: (ON STEREO)
        <i> � I'm glad you called,</i>
        <i> but I'm not home</i>

06:28.956 --> 06:31.323
       <i> � But I'll be back</i>
       <i> before too long</i>

06:31.325 --> 06:32.758
      BOTH:
      <i> � Wait for the beep</i>

06:32.760 --> 06:35.727
  <i> � You gotta leave your name</i>
  <i> you gotta leave your number</i>

06:35.729 --> 06:37.062
      <i> � Wait for the beep �</i>

06:37.064 --> 06:39.431
           (BEEPING)
 Al, don't join into
 their nonsense.

06:39.433 --> 06:43.168
 Listen... We have
 no answering-machine problems.

06:43.170 --> 06:44.903
 My message stays.

06:44.905 --> 06:46.638
 Please, just listen to reason.

06:46.640 --> 06:48.707
 The message you recorded
 is so bad,

06:48.709 --> 06:49.441
 our friends refuse to call.

06:49.443 --> 06:52.644
         The light is blinking.
         I must be doing
         something right.

06:52.646 --> 06:54.179
    POP POP:
    (ON ANSWERING MACHINE)
    <i> Hello. Is this Murray?</i>

06:54.181 --> 06:56.148
   <i> What? You got a robit</i>
   <i> taking your messages now?</i>

06:56.150 --> 06:59.384
      <i> Ooh, my highfalutin' son</i>
      <i> thinks he's better</i>
      <i> than everyone.</i>

06:59.386 --> 07:00.218
 I think it's Pop Pop.

07:00.220 --> 07:01.686
         <i> Well, you're not.</i>
         <i> You're a thief!</i>

07:01.688 --> 07:04.523
  <i> Don't think I forgot about</i>
  <i> that $17 you stole from me.</i>

07:04.525 --> 07:07.592
          Still with the $17!
          I can't take this!

07:07.594 --> 07:08.193
    (TAPE FAST-FORWARDING)

07:08.195 --> 07:10.262
      <i> My electric bill</i>
      <i> was the same every month,</i>

07:10.264 --> 07:11.963
      <i> but all of a sudden,</i>
      <i> it's $17 more.</i>

07:11.965 --> 07:13.732
   <i> Yeah, well, you do the math,</i>
   <i> genius!</i>

07:13.734 --> 07:15.367
               He's taking up
               the whole tape!

07:15.369 --> 07:15.967
      (TAPE FAST-FORWARDING)

07:15.969 --> 07:17.335
     <i> I know you were upset</i>
     <i> about your wedding toast,</i>

07:17.337 --> 07:19.838
  <i> but I really thought you</i>
  <i> preferred the company of men.</i>

07:19.840 --> 07:20.672
      (TAPE FAST-FORWARDING)

07:20.674 --> 07:21.740
    <i> You were an ugly baby.</i>
    <i> There, I said it.</i>

07:21.742 --> 07:25.177
             MURRAY: That's it!
 Well, at least he's talking
 to you. That's new.

07:25.179 --> 07:27.045
               Oh, we will talk
               but good.

07:27.047 --> 07:30.048
     Just he and I, man to man.

07:30.050 --> 07:31.716
        (KNOCK ON DOOR)

07:31.718 --> 07:33.752
              Ah, you.
              What do you want?

07:33.754 --> 07:35.887
 My dad paid me $20
 to set this up for you

07:35.889 --> 07:37.189
 so you won't miss
 his phone call.

07:37.191 --> 07:40.192
           Ah, so he'll pony up
           20 bucks for you,

07:40.194 --> 07:41.593
                and still
                I'm out my $17.

07:41.595 --> 07:44.095
 I don't know, man.
 Do you want
 the machine or not?

07:44.097 --> 07:45.564
           All right.
           I'll take the robit,

07:45.566 --> 07:47.032
             but only because
             I like free stuff.

07:47.034 --> 07:48.967
          ADULT ADAM:
          <i> As Erica did</i>
          <i> my dad's dirty work,</i>

07:48.969 --> 07:52.370
 <i> me and my new pals were having</i>
 <i> some good, clean fun.</i>

07:52.372 --> 07:54.639
 And that, my friend,
 is how you use Basic

07:54.641 --> 07:57.175
 to program
 a real-life booby.

07:57.177 --> 07:58.276
                    Whoa!

07:58.278 --> 08:00.545
       ADAM: So lifelike.

08:00.647 --> 08:03.348
        Scram! Me and this lady
        are gonna study

08:03.350 --> 08:05.584
              for health class,
              with our faces.

08:05.586 --> 08:07.919
 No way! We're allowed
 to be here at lunch.

08:07.921 --> 08:08.887
 Mr. Glascott says.

08:08.889 --> 08:11.022
       You're a ballsy,
       little nerd, aren't you?

08:11.024 --> 08:12.557
        Tell you what,
        I'm gonna let it slide,

08:12.559 --> 08:16.528
       but only because there's
       a broom closet for us
       right down the hall.

08:16.530 --> 08:17.696
            Later, nerd losers.

08:17.698 --> 08:19.231
 Look at them
 with their nerd thermoses.

08:19.233 --> 08:21.967
       GIRL: Like they're nerd
       construction workers.

08:21.969 --> 08:24.102
          (BOTH LAUGHING)

08:24.505 --> 08:27.205
 Excuse me.
 What did you just say
 about those nerd losers?

08:27.207 --> 08:30.575
           Uh, that they should
           drink out of their
           nerd thermoses?

08:30.577 --> 08:31.409
 Glascott's office now!

08:31.411 --> 08:33.979
    BEVERLY:
    So, what kind of punishment
    are we talking about here?

08:33.981 --> 08:37.482
 Suspension, expulsion,
 solitary confinement?

08:37.484 --> 08:40.085
 Do we do that?
 'Cause that's what I want.

08:40.087 --> 08:41.019
              Yeah. You two can
              go back to class,

08:41.020 --> 08:45.123
  and try not to be so accurate
  with your nerd insults
  next time.

08:45.125 --> 08:47.325
          Oh, and stay out
          of that broom closet.

08:47.327 --> 08:49.528
  Yeah, that's right.
  Old Glascott knows what's up!

08:49.530 --> 08:52.864
 Why did you let them go?
 They called my schmoo a nerd.

08:52.866 --> 08:56.535
     That's not on them.
     That's more on your schmoo
     for being one.

08:56.537 --> 08:59.104
 Hey, only I get to call
 my schmoo a schmoo.

08:59.106 --> 09:01.740
              The point is,
              Adam and his gang
              of computer dorks

09:01.742 --> 09:03.475
              don't even eat
              in the lunchroom.

09:03.477 --> 09:06.011
    That means they're not even
    on the social ladder.

09:06.013 --> 09:07.379
     You've got to do something
     about this.

09:07.381 --> 09:10.448
        If you don't help Adam,
        then you have failed
        as a mother.

09:10.450 --> 09:13.251
 But that is
 my greatest nightmare.

09:13.253 --> 09:14.586
 You gotta help me.
 Please.

09:14.588 --> 09:16.755
 I told him I'd respect
 his boundaries.

09:16.757 --> 09:18.690
 Guide me.
 It's what you're so good at.

09:18.692 --> 09:20.592
       I know you're playing me
       for a fool,

09:20.594 --> 09:23.028
      but this fool
      has low-grade depression.

09:23.030 --> 09:24.462
              So... I'll bite.

09:24.464 --> 09:27.499
   ADULT ADAM:
